The game garnered positive reviews following its release, and received the reputation of a Nintendo classic over time.<ref name="1UPSQ"/> Japanese game magazine ''[[Famitsu]]'' gave it a score of 28 out of 40.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=9072|title=ドラキュラII 呪いの封印 [ファミコン] / ファミ通.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924051511/http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=9072|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 1990, ''[[Nintendo Power]]''{{'}}s NES retrospective ''Pak Source'' gave ''Simon's Quest'' ratings of 4.5/5 for Graphic and Sound, 4/5 for Play Control, 4/5 for Challenge, and 4/5 for Theme Fun.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Pak Source|magazine=[[Nintendo Power]]|publisher=[[Nintendo of America]]|date=January 1990}}</ref> In 2008, ''Nintendo Power'' ranked it as the 15th best NES game, comparing it to ''[[Zelda II: The Adventure of Link]]'' in how it successfully added role-playing video game elements to its series.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 2008 |title=Nintendo Power – The 20th Anniversary Issue! |volume=231 |series= [[Nintendo Power]] |issue=231 |page=71 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[San Francisco, California]] |medium=Magazine}}</ref> In a 1997 ''Castlevania'' retrospective, ''[[GamePro]]'' called it "an excellent time-killer, and much longer than the first ''Castlevania''".<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Castlevania Rises from the Grave|magazine=[[GamePro]] |issue=108|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=September 1997|page=34}}</ref> ''[[IGN]]'' called ''Simon's Quest'' the "perfect game to play during 1989". It praised the theme of exploration, acknowledged the evolution of the series, and lauded its graphical and audio presentation.<ref name="IGNReview" />

Retrospective reviews of ''Simon's Quest'' have been more critical. Points of criticism were made about backtracking, easy bosses, and the day-to-night cycle. A common complaint was its English localization, with cryptic and poorly translated clues from [[non-player character]]s.<ref name="IGNReview"/> Former ''Castlevania'' producer, [[Koji Igarashi]], revealed that the NPCs in the Japanese version were deliberate liars.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.g-wie-gorilla.de/content/view/233/18 |title=Interview with Koji Igarashi & Michiru Yamane |publisher=Gie Wie Gorilla |access-date=2008-07-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624222202/http://www.g-wie-gorilla.de/content/view/233/18 |archive-date=2008-06-24 }}</ref> [[GameSpot]] said that the subtle hints from the Japanese version were lost in translation, such as the infamous line "hit Deborah Cliff with your head to make a hole".<ref name="GSReview"/>
[[Active Gaming Media]] showed that the Japanese text was similarly misleading, but further described where and how an accurate hint from the Japanese game was lost.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.activegamingmedia.com/news/resolving-a-translation-mystery-castlevania-ii-simon%E2%80%99s-quest-sunday-ja |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310164141/http://www.activegamingmedia.com/news/resolving-a-translation-mystery-castlevania-ii-simon%E2%80%99s-quest-sunday-ja |archive-date=2011-03-10 |author=Anthony Teixeira |title=Resolving a Translation Mystery – Castlevania II |publisher=[[Active Gaming Media]] |access-date=2010-01-10}}</ref> Further criticism stemmed from some of the game's puzzles, which have no clues at all,<ref name=":1" /> such as a scenario where Simon must summon a tornado at Deborah Cliff with the Red Crystal.<ref name="GSReview"/> [[1UP.com]] said the game required a [[Strategy guide|walkthrough]] because of its non-explanatory nature.<ref name="1UPSQ">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3164033 |title=Retro Roundup 10/29: Castlevania, Spyro, Magician Lord |website=[[1UP.com]] |access-date=2008-08-09 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> ''[[Game Informer]]'' said that while the game is important in gaming history, it was still a polarizing game due to "cryptic puzzles" and other difficult elements.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ranking The Castlevania Bloodline |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/04/04/ranking-the-castlevania-bloodline.aspx |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |last=Turi |first=Tim |date=2012-04-04 |access-date=2013-12-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507064948/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/04/04/ranking-the-castlevania-bloodline.aspx |archive-date=2013-05-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Legacy===
''Simon's Quest'' is the second ''Castlevania'' game to depart from linear gameplay, following ''[[Vampire Killer]]'' for the [[MSX2]] in 1986, and instead feature a non-linear explorative world. This design has been compared to Nintendo's ''Metroid'' series,<ref name="CV1up">{{cite web |author=Kurt Kalata |date=2006-07-26 |title=Tales from the Crypt: Castlevania's 20th Anniversary Blow-Out |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=1&cId=3152109 |work=1UP.com |access-date=2008-08-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522124136/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=1&cId=3152109 |archive-date=2011-05-22 }}</ref> yielding the [[Metroidvania]] subgenre. The game's exploration system and ideas introduced adventure elements to the series, and it would heavily influence future games.<ref name="IGNCVRetro">{{cite web |author=Mark Bozon |date=2007-01-18 |url=http://gameboy.ign.com/articles/756/756724p2.html |title=Castlevania: The Retrospective |website=[[IGN]] |access-date=2008-07-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928192628/http://gameboy.ign.com/articles/756/756724p2.html |archive-date=2008-09-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first game that drew inspiration from it was ''[[Castlevania: Symphony of the Night]]''.<ref name="CV1up"/> Igarashi, ''Symphony of the Night''{{'}}s assistant director,  said the critical reaction to ''Simon's Quest'' and its gameplay allowed the game to be pitched to Konami.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/castlevania-symphony-of-the-night-wouldnt-have-happened-without-castlevania-2-simons-quest | title = Castlevania: Symphony of the Night Wouldn't Have Happened Without Castlevania 2: Simon's Quest | first = Nadia | last = Oxford | date = September 7, 2018 | access-date = September 7, 2018 | work = [[USGamer]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181001030938/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/castlevania-symphony-of-the-night-wouldnt-have-happened-without-castlevania-2-simons-quest | archive-date = October 1, 2018 | url-status = live | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''Simon's Quest'' would be directly referenced in later ''Castlevania'' games. In the [[Game Boy Advance]] entry, ''[[Castlevania: Harmony of Dissonance]]'', the protagonist [[List of Castlevania characters#Juste Belmont|Juste Belmont]] recounts when his grandfather Simon had to go search for Dracula's body parts. In the game, the player must find them again.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Castlevania: Harmony of Dissonance|developer=Konami |publisher=Konami|date=2002-06-06 |platform=Game Boy Advance|level=Corridor in the Air}}</ref>

==In other media==
[[File:Nintendopower002.jpg|thumb|The front page of ''Nintendo Power'' #2 received complaints from parents.]]

Upon its release, ''Simon's Quest'' was briefly the subject of controversy when it received strong publicity in the second issue of ''Nintendo Power''. Its front page had a costumed model dressed as Simon Belmont, holding Dracula's severed head. This cover provoked many telephone complaints from parents of children who purchased the magazine,<ref name="NP2">''50 Issues of Nintendo Power'': Worst Cover: Castlevania II – Vol. 2 showed Simon Belmont holding Dracula's head. Kids had nightmares and so did our phone reps who dealt with the complaints. – ''Nintendo Power'', Vol. 50, p.36</ref> stating that it gave their children nightmares. ''Nintendo Power'' covered this in issue 50, citing this as its worst cover.<ref name="NP2"/> ''Simon's Quest'' was referenced in a following issue in a ''[[Nintendo Power#Nester|Howard and Nester]]'' comic strip.<ref>''Nintendo Power'' November/December 1988</ref>

''Simon's Quest'' was followed by the release of merchandise. In 1988, [[Tiger Electronics]] released a handheld game and an LCD wristwatch based on ''Simon's Quest''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/history_castlevania/p16_02.html|title=The History of Castlevania – Related Games|website=[[GameSpot]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726155113/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/history_castlevania/p16_02.html|archive-date=2008-07-26|url-status=dead|access-date=2008-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vgmuseum.com/mrp/2/cv2watch-main.htm|title=Castlevania 2: Simon's Quest – LCD Wristwatch|publisher=VGMuseum.com|access-date=2008-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080923141331/http://www.vgmuseum.com/mrp/2/cv2watch-main.htm|archive-date=2008-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref> Promotional collector's cards were also available in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://castlevaniadungeon.net/Images/Scans/CV2/cv2-card.jpg|title=Castlevania 2 Cards|publisher=ClassicGaming.com. [[GameSpy]]|access-date=2008-09-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612143447/http://castlevaniadungeon.net/Images/Scans/CV2/cv2-card.jpg|archive-date=2010-06-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, a figurine of Simon's appearance from ''Simon's Quest'' was included as a [[Pre-order|pre-order bonus]] for ''[[Castlevania: The Dracula X Chronicles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qj.net/qjnet/psp/castlevania-dracula-x-chronicles-with-simon-belmont-figure.html|title=Castlevania: Dracula X Chronicles with Simon Belmont figure|date=2007-10-08|work=QJ|publisher=Caputo Media|access-date=2014-05-02}}</ref>

''[[Worlds of Power]]'', a 1990s series of books with stories based on Nintendo games, has a novel about ''Simon's Quest''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://castlevaniadungeon.net/features/book.html|title=Castlevania 2: Worlds of Power Book|publisher=ClassicGaming.com. [[GameSpy]]|access-date=2008-08-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109045531/http://www.castlevaniadungeon.net/features/book.html|archive-date=2010-01-09|url-status=live}}</ref> It was written by [[Christopher Howell]], and the series was produced by [[Seth Godin]]. It departs from the original plot and introduces characters not seen in the game, including junior high school student Timothy Bradley, a video gamer who crosses over into the world of ''Simon's Quest'' and assists Simon in looking for Dracula's body parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3152540|title=8-Bit Lit: Behind the Worlds of Power Books based on Nintendo Entertainment System games|last=Struck|first=Shawn|author2=Scott Sharkey|date=2006-08-03|website=[[1UP.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605020331/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3152540|archive-date=2011-06-05|url-status=dead|access-date=2009-07-14}}</ref>

